definition.value: A metal cation comprising samarium in the +3 oxidation state.
The complex formed between iron(III) and citrate.
A compound of zinc and chloride ions in the ratio 1:2. It exists in four crystalline forms, in each of which the Zn(2+) ions are trigonal planar coordinated to four chloride ions.
A member of the class of flavones having one or more glycosyl residues attached at unspecified positions.
A compound formally derived from ammonia by replacing one, two or three hydrogen atoms by organyl groups.

The dihydrate form of the calcium salt of fenoprofen. A non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drug, it is used for the management of mild to moderate pain and for the relief of pain and inflammation associated with disorders such as arthritis. It is pharmacologically similar to aspirin, but causes less gastrointestinal bleeding.
A 3-pyranone with a 4,5-double bond carrying a hydroxy group at position 4 and a hydroxymethyl group at position 6.
A 4-pyranone with a 2,3-double bond carrying a hydroxy group at position 3 and a hydroxymethyl group at position 6.

The anhydrous form of the calcium salt of fenprofen. The dihydrate form is used as a non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drug for the management of mild to moderate pain and for the relief of pain and inflammation associated with disorders such as arthritis.
Any anion formed by loss of a proton from a steroid acid.
Any member of the class of benzaldehydes in which the phenyl ring is substituted by two hydroxy groups.
A dihydroxybenzaldehyde that is resorcinol which has been substituted by a formyl group para to one of the hydroxy groups.
A quinolone that is 4-oxo-1,4-dihydroquinoline which is substituted at positions 1, 3, 6 and 7 by ethyl, carboxy, fluorine, and 4-methylpiperazin-1-yl groups, respectively.
Any dicarboxylic acid carrying a hydroxy group on the carbon atom at position alpha to the carboxy group.
Heterocyclic compound with sulfur and nitrogen in the ring.

A magnesium salt resulting from the formal reaction of magnesium hydroxide with 2 mol eq. of esomeprazole. An inhibitor of gastric acid secretion, it is used for the treatment of gastro-oesophageal reflux disease, dyspepsia, peptic ulcer disease, and Zollinger-Ellison syndrome.
Mononuclear cations derived by addition of a hydron to a mononuclear parent hydride of the pnictogen, chalcogen and halogen families.
